{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti 5.155 is not present in the Falsafa corpus edition of the text (which covers 12 chapters in verse layout, with Chapter 5 focusing on dietary rules, forbidden foods, and purificatory penances for twice-born men).**[^1] Searches for the verse reference, including exact phrases like \"5.155\" or \"Mn 5.155,\" returned no matches across the work.[^2]\n\nHowever, Manu does prescribe rules for women elsewhere, most notably in **Chapter 9 (on laws of union, separation, inheritance, and duties)**. Verse 9.3 (paragraph p-233021) states that women must always be kept in dependence:\n\n> Her father protects her in childhood, her husband protects her in youth, and her sons protect her in old age; **a woman is never fit for independence**.[^3]\n\nThis establishes lifelong male guardianship as their prescribed duty and status, echoed in surrounding verses (e.g., 9.2 on keeping women \"under one's own control,\" and 9.5–7 on men's obligation to protect wives diligently).[^4] Women are assigned household roles like managing wealth and cooking (9.11), but no autonomy.[^5]\n\nIf this refers to a different edition or verse numbering (standard Manusmṛti 5.155 concerns penance durations after meals, unrelated to women), the corpus does not cover it. Chapter 5 incidentally bars twice-born men from food \"touched by a menstruating woman\" (echoed from 4.208).[^6] For related texts, see Yājñavalkya Smṛti 1.84 (similar protection rule).[^7]",
